  <h1>Documentation</h1>
  
  <p class="lead">
    Zen is a markdown extension language for multi-agent systems. It's designed to be 
    readable as natural prose, parseable by deterministic tools, and interpretable by LLMs.
  </p>

  <h2>What is Zen?</h2>
  
  <p>
    Zen extends standard markdown with constructs for expressing agent behaviors, 
    skill composition, and orchestration patterns. A zen document (with <code>.zen.md</code> extension) 
    is both valid markdown and a parseable program.
  </p>

  <h2>Key Features</h2>
  
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Types</strong> — Semantic hints that guide LLM interpretation</li>
    <li><strong>Variables</strong> — Named values with type annotations</li>
    <li><strong>References</strong> — Wiki-style links to other skills</li>
    <li><strong>Semantic Markers</strong> — LLM-interpreted placeholders</li>
    <li><strong>Control Flow</strong> — CAPS keywords for loops and conditionals</li>
    <li><strong>Composition</strong> — Skill delegation with parameters</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Two-Layer Model</h2>
  
  <p>
    Zen uses a two-layer architecture:
  </p>
  
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Source Format</strong> — Human-authored, uses compact syntax</li>
    <li><strong>Compiled Format</strong> — Optimized for LLM consumption</li>
  </ul>
  
  <p>
    The compiler transforms types, references, and semantic markers into LLM-friendly formats.
  </p>

  <h2>Getting Started</h2>
  
  <p>
    Ready to dive in? Start with the <a href="/docs/getting-started">Quick Start guide</a> 
    to install zen and write your first skill, or explore <a href="/examples">examples</a> 
